The Industrials Sunday Section
We summarize industrial news, events, and developments.

Data Center Reads. NVDA data center revenues increased \(56\%\) Y/Y in F2Q as it continues to ramp Blackwell architecture, which now accounts for half of its data center revenue. Mgmt noted a GB300 run rate of 1,000 racks per week, which should accelerate through 3Q as additional capacity comes online. NVDA sees the potential for \(3 - 4T\) of AI infrastructure spending over the next five years (link). MRVL saw data center revenue up \(3\%\) Q/Q and \(69\%\) Y/Y in 2Q, with expectations for data center revenue to be flat Q/Q and up mid- \(30\%\) Y/Y in 3Q. AI- driven cloud workloads accounted for \(90\% +\) of datacenter revenue. Mgmt. highlighted that custom AI design engagements are at all- time high (link).

Consumer Confidence Index. The consumer has remained relatively consistent this summer with concerns on tariffs and higher inflation. At 97, the current reading is roughly halfway between the Nov. 2024 highs of 113 and the 86 reading that occurred following the Liberation Day in April. Discretionary spending intentions decreased, and vacation intentions fell for the second straight month.
Exhibit 1 - Aug. Consumer Confidence Index decreased 1.3pts M/M
Source: The Conference Board
Exhibit 2 - Aug. Consumer Present and Future Indexes decreased 1.6pts M/M and 1.2pts M/M, respectively
Source: The Conference Board

Capex Finance Index. July ELFA CapEx Finance Index increased \(1.7\%\) M/M, with the equipment finance industry remaining stable despite economic volatility, and on pace to be one of the best years despite some cooling from the record volume in 2024. ELFA highlighted that financial conditions are healthy, with credit approvals increasing, losses decreasing, and the delinquency rate remaining stable.
Exhibit 3 - New business volume for equipment leases and loans increased \(1.7\%\) M/M, but decreased \(6.3\%\) Y/Y in July
Exhibit 4 - The credit approval rate increased 3.2pts Y/Y and 1.8pts M/M in July

New Home Sales. New home sales decreased 60bps M/M and \(8.2\%\) Y/Y in July to an annual 652K pace. Existing home sales increased \(2\%\) M/M to \(\sim 4m\) units, the third lowest reading this year.
Exhibit 5 - New home sales decreased 60bps M/M in July
Source:US Census Bureau
Exhibit 6 - New home sales decreased 8.2% Y/Y in July
Source:US Census Bureau
Exhibit 7 - Existing home sales increased 2% M/M in July
Source:US Census Bureau
Exhibit 8 - Existing home sales increased 75bps Y/Y in July
Source:US Census Bureau
Komtex Data. Komatsu construction equipment saw July NA avg. monthly hours of machine use up 6.6% Y/Y (vs - 0.2% in June).
Exhibit 9 - July average monthly hours of machine use increased 6.6% Y/Y in NA
Exhibit 10 - July average monthly hours of machine use increased 3.3% Y/Y and 60bps Y/Y in Japan and Europe, respectively

NRA Index. The July NRA index decreased modestly with operators continuing to report higher sales but lower traffic. Operators reported a net increase in SSS in July (net 6% reporting sales growth vs. 8% in June), while traffic continued to decline but at a more moderated rate (net 6% vs. net 11% in June). Operators are less optimistic about sales growth in 6M, with net 2% expecting growth (vs. prev. 11%).
Exhibit 11 - July current SSS index declined 20bps M/M
Exhibit 12 - July SSS Expectation Index increased 89bps M/M

Macro. Texas mfg. activity declined 2.7pts M/M in August. Production declined M/M though remained well above its historical average, and shipments were the highest in over three years. Orders turned positive for the first time since January. Richmond mfg. activity increased 13pts M/M in August, reaching a 5-month high, though remained in negative territory. Orders, shipments, and employment all improved sequentially, though remained negative. KC mfg. activity remained flat M/M in August, with durable manufacturing mostly flat and nondurable manufacturing declining slightly. Most indexes increased M/M, except for the backlog of orders, new export orders and inventories. The Chicago Business Barometer decreased 5.6pts M/M to 41.5 in Aug., erasing most of July's increase driven by sharp declines in orders, backlogs, employment, and production, partially offset by growth in supplier deliveries. US capital goods orders (ex. A&D) increased 1.1% M/M in July, with growth in: electrical equipment (+2.0%), machinery (+1.8%), primary metals (+1.5%), fabricated metals (+0.7%), and computer-related orders (+0.6%).

EU industrial confidence decreased 0.2pts M/M in Aug. on lower production expectations, export orders and selling price expectations. Sentiment among German mfg. companies declined 0.3pts M/M in August as there are still no indications of order intake growth.
Exhibit 13 - Aug. Kansas City current business activity index remained flat M/M; while the future business activity index increased 3pt M/M
Exhibit 14 - Aug. Kansas City current and future new orders indexes increased 3pts M/M and 6pts M/M, respectively
Source: Federal Reserve Exhibit 15 - Aug. Richmond current business activity index increased 13pts M/M, while future business activity decreased 8pts M/M

Marvell Technology Group Ltd.  Price Target: \(80 implies 18x our CY27 EPS of\) 4.48.
- Share loss in the optical DSP market or the market moving towards direct drive.
- Slower ramp of AI ASIC wins.
- Slower design win momentum and slower than expected ramp in the custom ASIC business. Margin degradation from overseas competition.
Price Target: \(205 implies 30x our CY27E EPS of\) 6.82.
- Emerging competitive threats from INTC, AMD, and internally designed ASICs from Hyperscalers take share and pressure ASPs.
- Slowing datacenter capital spending from Enterprises and Hyperscalers.
- Slower-than-expected ramp of Automotive platform.

Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion. Stocks will be added as new opportunities arise and removed when the reason for inclusion changes, the stock has met its desired return, if it is no longer rated Buy and/or if it triggers a stop loss. Stocks having 120 day volatility in the bottom quartile of S&P stocks will continue to have a \(15\%\) stop loss, and the remainder will have a \(20\%\) stop. Franchise Picks are not intended to represent a recommended portfolio of stocks and is not sector based, but we may note where we believe a Pick falls within an investment style such as growth or value.
